  56	## Casks
  57	
  58	Casks use the `brew-cask:` manager. mise fetches cask metadata directly from
  59	the Homebrew cask API (or from tap API metadata), downloads the artifact,
  60	verifies its sha256 when the cask provides one, extracts the archive, and
  61	installs app bundles into `/Applications` while recording the version under
  62	`<prefix>/Caskroom`.
  63	
  64	```toml
  65	[bootstrap.packages]
  66	"brew-cask:firefox" = "latest"
  67	"brew-cask:homebrew/cask/visual-studio-code" = "latest"
  68	```
  69	
  70	`brew-cask` currently supports app-bundle casks (`app` artifacts), binary casks
  71	(`binary` artifacts), and simple macOS installer packages (`pkg` artifacts)
  72	from dmg and common archive formats. Binary artifacts are staged in the Caskroom
  73	and linked into the Homebrew prefix, usually under `<prefix>/bin`. Package
  74	installers run through mise's normal system-package sudo path, so non-interactive
  75	runs never hang waiting for a password. Pkg casks must include `pkgutil` receipt
  76	IDs in their `uninstall` or `zap` metadata so mise can verify installed state
  77	after the installer writes files outside the Caskroom. For casks with lifecycle
  78	hooks, mise fetches the sha256-verified cask Ruby source pinned by the API
  79	metadata and runs supported `preflight`/`postflight` hooks through its own Cask
  80	DSL shim, without delegating to Homebrew. Casks that require custom installer
  81	choices, services, unsupported hook DSL, or other cask artifact types fail with
  82	a clear unsupported artifact error instead of delegating to Homebrew. Generated
  83	shell completions are not installed.
  84	
  85	This exists because shared-library packages — postgres, ffmpeg, imagemagick,
  86	php — fundamentally can't be served by mise's per-project backends like
  87	`aqua:` or `github:`: their bottles are built against fixed install paths and
  88	a shared dependency tree. Installing them at Homebrew's canonical prefix is
  89	what makes them work.
  90	
 225	`mise bootstrap packages upgrade` re-resolves the configured formulae against the
 226	formulae.brew.sh API and pours any whose current version differs from the
 227	linked keg — the new keg replaces the old one and the links are repointed,
 228	the same dance `brew upgrade` does. Since bottles only exist for a formula's
 229	current version, "upgrade" and "install the current bottle" are the same
 230	operation.
 231	
 232	## Limitations
 233	
 234	- **Cask artifact coverage is intentionally narrow.** `brew-cask` supports
 235	  app bundles, binary artifacts, and simple pkg installers from dmg and common
 236	  archive formats. Other artifact types, pkg installers without `pkgutil` IDs,
 237	  and pkg installers with custom choices fail explicitly.
 238	- **`brew services` is not implemented.**
 239	- **Cask import/prune is not implemented.** `import` and `prune` are formulae-only
